title: For Sale:  FN SCAR 17S
postcontent: FN Herstal SCAR 17S black. This is the 7.62X51/.308 Winchester, one in twelve twist model. This is the one that will reach out and touch someone. I'll let the stock photos tell the story but I'll just go over the features as she sits here on my lap. The upper receiver has an integral 16" rail. The flip up rear sight is windage and elevation adjustable. It allows you to flip between either of two different apertures. It can be moved forward or back on the upper rail. The flip up front sight is mounted on the gas block and is also windage and elevation adjustable. The post is square in cross section and about 1/16" in width. The elevation adjustment is similar to that of the M16. The 16.25" barrel is free floating; has a cold hammer forged, hardchromed bore; and its muzzle is threaded 5/8" X 24tpi having what I expect to be a flash hider, although it suggests it might function as a brake as well. I couldn't find the answer to that on the FN website. The forearm has three accessory rails. There are ambidextrous integral forward and rear of receiver sling attachment points. They were designed for tactical slings, not traditional high power shooting slings. Shame on them. Oh well, ideas change, eh? There is a bolt hold open reminiscent of the M16. The magazine release is ambidextrous as is the safety/selector. Two positions only....sorry. The buttstock collapses and folds to create an overall length between 28.5" and 38.5". It has an adjustable cheek piece that elevates to fine tune your spot weld/sight picture. I like that because I tend to "crane" forward and take a tight weld which actually puts me low on the iron sights. With the cheek piece up, I get a perfect sight picture when I'm settled in the way I prefer. I'll bet this would be fun to shoot at distance. FN does brag about the long range accuracy, although it doesn't have what one would consider a target trigger. The pull is military heavy. The rifle weighs 8.0 lbs empty. An owner's manual, a lock, and one 20rd magazine are included. I have spare magazines available to the winner of the auction. That's it. What do you think? I will be glad to sell to you Americans in California or other oppressive states.
